      <byline class="print_byline">By Florence Fabricant</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Fabricant, Florence</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mashish Foods in Israel produces tasty gefilte fish in cans, needing no refrigeration until opened; photo; Dean &amp; DeLuca is selling improved Oreo cookies and Hostess cupcakes; photo; Allison and Margaret Engel, who are twins, revise 'Food Finds,' comprehensive guide to American regional foods; photo; Asia Society establishes food web site; drawing (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Putting gefilte fish on the table often involves opening a jar. Now there is a tastier choice: canned. Mashish Foods in Bnei Brak, Israel, packs four ovals of fish with carrot slices and fish jelly in a rectangular metal box, which needs no refrigeration until it has been opened.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Putting gefilte fish on the table often involves opening a jar. Now there is a tastier choice: canned. Mashish Foods in Bnei Brak, Israel, packs four ovals of fish with carrot slices and fish jelly in a rectangular metal box, which needs no refrigeration until it has been opened.</p>
        <p>The fish is kosher and delicious, provided that you prefer it a tad sweet. It is a good idea to chill it before serving. Each package is $5.99 at Fairway, 2127 Broadway (74th Street) and 2328 12th Avenue (132nd Street).</p>
        <p>FOOD STUFF</p>
      </block>
